<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-the-same-direction" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Relative Speeds of Objects Moving in the Same Direction</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_t8q1z86q">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_yfbup52i">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_egua6eq8">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4arasotc">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ove7ab2t">
                        2.10 Linear Motion
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_b15fpofi">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8hu0guqq">
                        Determine relative speed of two moving bodies in different situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l1hx4ovh" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_99wl3lvr">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yvz13nyz" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_m9187iuo">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_uf1md4wb" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_50b92w34"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_8s4xenot">
                        <p xml:id="auto_jvfwtxcm">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Relative speed is how fast one object is moving compared to another. When two objects move in the same direction, relative speed equals the difference of their individual speeds.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_8oiewu1u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_pbu7g2qe">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate relative speed for objects moving in the same direction. Convert between km/h and m/s. Determine time to overtake using <m>\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Relative Speed}}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_alkhguox">
                        <p xml:id="auto_g0jtxmwl">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world overtaking problems involving cyclists, motorcycles, cars, and trucks on the same road.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_0scasm4t">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-the-same-direction.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_of34zr1w">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-the-same-direction.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_gba66np7">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_kwkv0v71">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xs4u36zy">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_huqhs9oq">
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_47suw1bp">
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_v7183lmm">
                    Toy car (pulled by string), string, stopwatch, measuring tape (10 metres), pen and paper, calculator
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_1bxhcfev">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_i5zhou2l">
                    Circulate among groups, ensuring safe movement and accurate timing. Offer guidance on recording results but let students discover the relative speed concept themselves.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p xml:id="auto_fhwafgcf">
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wjvqboiy">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_h3d3yoy0">Ensure the straight pathway is clear and safe before the activity begins.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1fkhhavc">Remind groups to measure carefully and record times precisely.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_90sr4cdq">Prompt: <q>If both objects are going in the same direction, does the faster one get further away or closer?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_v7h3gv7m">After the race, ask each group to share their calculated speeds and relative speed.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_l48k0spp">
            <alert>Discussion Prompts (after group work):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ylilxmyp">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_qlq271lq">Who moved faster? Was the student walking faster or slower than the toy car?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ohsgtrwz">Why might one object have moved faster than the other?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pnkmzssf">What is the relative speed? How does the speed of each participant relate to the other?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5z7jo855">Did they move away from each other, or did they stay the same distance apart?</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <activity xml:id="auto_hdn6c1xl">
        <p xml:id="auto_apra5lcf">
            <em><term>Work in Groups.</term></em>
        </p>
    
        <p xml:id="auto_k8px5yvo">
            In this activity you are required to follow each step as listed.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_u7kfjdkz">
            <term>What you need:</term>
            <ul xml:id="auto_f1eu2m9u" cols="2">
                <li xml:id="auto_lp3s0r8q">
                    <p xml:id="auto_k1nrsif0">
                        Toy car (that can be pulled by a string).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_clnw9mdq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_b3icc13o">
                        String (long enough for the car to travel a sufficient distance).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ovaf6rba">
                    <p xml:id="auto_475yatb7">
                        Stopwatch or timer
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qbo4optn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jep4yffg">
                        Measuring tape or marked distance on the ground (e.g., 10 meters)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hyl0xilq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_eq02m78h">
                        Pen and paper (for recording results)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_su9ljd8t">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2yrycxj3">
                        Observers (to track the race and help evaluate results)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0ynwmnrm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_4ilojhq4">
                        Calculator (optional, for calculations)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <term>Steps:</term>
            <ol xml:id="auto_m92od9th" marker="(i)">
                <li xml:id="auto_5w492yna">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cg8znbzz">
                        Find a straight line or pathway that is clear and suitable for the race (
                            a hallway, classroom floor, long corridor or outside on a field).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zpa192ri">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ol6a2b5e">
                        Measure out a distance for the race, such as 10 meters. 
                        You can use a measuring tape or use a marked area to set the starting and 
                        finishing points.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mmmxnjt4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9n76q3wk">
                        Mark the starting line and the finish line clearly, 
                        so both the toy car and the student know where to start and end.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pgplhyd2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dlm3bp7w">
                        Attach one end of the string securely to the toy car.
                        The other end of the string should be held by a participant or fixed to 
                        an anchor (like a pole or sturdy object) so that when the student pulls the string, 
                        the car moves along the line and test the toy car to ensure that it moves 
                        easily along the straight path when the string is pulled.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rom6di8a">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3fnrpq6h">
                        You will have two participants: one student (who will walk) and one toy car 
                        (which will be pulled by the string).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_srv4epdp">
                    <p xml:id="auto_whhybnqy">
                        Assign at least one observer to track the race. The observer(s) will help measure 
                        the time it takes for each participant (the student and the toy car) to reach the 
                        finish line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bwtwm7u2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_8sh5rojj">
                        Place the student and the toy at the starting line. The student should be 
                        ready to walk at a constant speed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wbqz4uvm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kss2kqoa">
                        On the count of "Go!", the student starts walking in a straight line towards 
                        the finish line. 
                        At the same time, the person holding the string should start pulling the toy 
                        car in the same direction (straight line) at a constant speed. 
                        The toy car should be pulled in a way that resembles a consistent movement, 
                        not too fast or too slow.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_76iq6a1r">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9udguz01">
                        The observers should start the stopwatch as soon as both participants begin 
                        moving and stop it when either the student or the toy car reaches the finish line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4z7efpod">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9zully0i">
                        Record the time taken by both the student and the toy car to reach the finish line. 
                        If you have more than one observer, make sure they agree on the recorded times.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jfxr79cu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_483kl6x9">
                        After the race, you need to calculate the relative speed between the student 
                        and the toy car.
                        <ul xml:id="auto_ghc0st6h">
                            <li xml:id="auto_mk6v8zan">
                                <p xml:id="auto_0vsfnky4">
                                    Let's say the student took <m>T1</m> seconds to cover the distance 
                                    (<m>10</m> meters), and the toy took <m>T2</m> seconds to cover same distance
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_92imqz0w">
                                <p xml:id="auto_41eqiu90">
                                    The speed of the student is:
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}} \amp = \frac{10}{\text{T1} \, \text{seconds}}  </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    The speed of the toy car is:
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}} \amp = \frac{10}{\text{T2} \, \text{seconds}}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ohymwkyb">
                                <p xml:id="auto_5uovhzoo">
                                    If the student and the toy car are moving in the same direction, 
                                    the relative speed can be given as:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_rr9c8xsm">
                                    Relative  speed  = Speed of Toy Car - Speed of Student 
                                    
                                </p>
                            </li>                               
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jrm4c1b3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ymfw9762">
                        Compare and share your fndings with other groups  of both the student and the toy car.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7hbh6zfa">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tqo68cco">
                        Discuss;
                        <ol xml:id="auto_5ld8ac8m" marker="(a).">
                            <li xml:id="auto_j93wr6iv">
                                <p xml:id="auto_f3m01roo">
                                    Who moved faster? Was the student walking faster or slower than the toy car?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_bct5qos0">
                                <p xml:id="auto_314xnihx">
                                    Why one object might have moved faster than the other. 
                                    Did the toy car move faster because it was pulled, or was the student 
                                    faster in their walking?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ba6fzinn">
                                <p xml:id="auto_dfgjwup7">
                                    The relative speed: 
                                    How does the speed of each participant relate to the other? 
                                    Did they move away from each other, or did they move closer together?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vf59ih8f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_arie94vt">
                        Now try the activity in different conditions or compare vraious 
                        speed by repeating the race multiple times.
                        <ul xml:id="auto_irww2943">
                            <li xml:id="auto_9tgrzp9q">
                                <p xml:id="auto_qaehgxnk">
                                    Have the student walk faster or slower.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_nu5g2iul">
                                <p xml:id="auto_4ivl0jcv">
                                    Change the length of the race to see how it affects the results.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1vxxl4xf">
                                <p xml:id="auto_4nvusp4o">
                                    Adjust how fast the toy car is pulled.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>

    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_z79p4nuh">
        <p xml:id="auto_q1sn7xzk">
           <alert>Definition:</alert> 
           Relative speed is how fast one object is moving compared to another object.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o5cikgnd">
            <alert>Formula for Same Direction:</alert>When two bodies move in the same direction at different
            speeds, their relative speed is the difference between the individual speeds. 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_749sugfz">
            Relative Speed <m>=</m> Speed of Faster Object - Speed of Slower Object
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_18l84z2x">
            <alert>Converting Units:</alert>
            To convert <m>km/h</m> to <m>m/s</m>, multiply by <m>\frac{1000}{3600}</m> (or divide by 3.6)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_x1foxill">
            <alert>Time to Overtake:</alert>
            <m>\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Relative Speed}}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bn8r5dco">
           <alert>Key Insight:</alert> 
           The faster object will eventually overtake the slower one when moving in the same direction.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_yukdz6ze">
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4mqvlfjr">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_04ckhubh">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_fip4g13g">Connect to the experiment: <q>You found that the relative speed was the difference between the two speeds — this works whenever objects move in the same direction.</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iru2oy9o">Emphasise the unit conversion step: converting km/h to m/s is essential when distances are in metres.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kcp8fzz0">Use the interactive simulation to reinforce concepts visually before moving to worked examples.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7sfgzmqp">Common misconception: students may try to add speeds for same-direction motion. Stress that subtraction applies because both objects cover ground in the same direction.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exploration xml:id="exploration-relative-speed-same-direction">
        <title>Relative Speeds in the Same Direction</title>
        <introduction xml:id="auto_gieanfu8">
            <p xml:id="auto_2o8gg1a8">
                In this activity, you will investigate how the distance between two moving objects changes over time. 
                Before you begin, please review the <xref ref="instructions-relative-speed" text="custom">instructions below </xref> for this simulation.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <figure xml:id="fig-relative-speed-three-panel">
            <caption>3-Panel Interactive: Relative Speed Simulation</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-relative-speed" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/relative-speed-same-direction.js">
                <sidebyside width="85%" margins="5%">
                    <stack>
                        <slate xml:id="box_controls" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:1" />
                        <slate xml:id="box_road" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:3" />
                        <slate xml:id="box_actions" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:1"/>
                    </stack>
                </sidebyside>
                <instructions xml:id="instructions-relative-speed">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cb1mf2oi">
                        <ol>
                            <li xml:id="auto_9lit3m0t">Drag the red and blue points on the axis in the middle panel to set their starting positions.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ju9f99vd">Adjust the sliders in the top panel to set the speeds for Car A (Red) and Car B (Blue).</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_k99lgsed">Click <q>Start</q> in the bottom panel to begin the animation.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ao1ylpon">Observe the <em>Relative Speed</em> and <em>Distance Covered</em> readouts. The simulation will pause automatically if the cars meet.</li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>

                    <p xml:id="auto_91jyz0ks">
                        Use the interactive tool to investigate the following scenarios:
                        <ol>
                            <li xml:id="auto_aqfql11l">
                                <p xml:id="auto_u4sa6jrd">
                                    Set both Car A and Car B to the exact same speed (e.g., <m>10</m> m/s). Start the animation. What happens to the "Relative Speed" readout? Does the distance gap between them ever change?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_q443hwtw">
                                <p xml:id="auto_03zkdwli">
                                    Set Car A (the rear car) to a higher speed than Car B. Observe the "Distance Covered" labels. Even though Car A starts behind, why does its "Distance Covered" increase faster than Car B's?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_jl9xqy7u">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ihvp3odu">
                                    Set Car A to a <em>lower</em> speed than Car B. Predict whether the "Cars Met!" message will ever appear. Why is the relative speed still a positive number even though the cars are getting further apart?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

