    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_x18mzwsu">
            Guide students through the worked examples below.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9sww0xqq">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2wgf0gfp">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_49pcqyn0">For each example, ask students to identify: Who is faster? What is the gap? Then set up the relative speed calculation.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mj2zlgnm">Emphasise the three-step process: (1) find relative speed, (2) convert units if needed, (3) apply <m>\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Relative Speed}}</m>.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_odalj874">Encourage students to estimate answers before calculating, to build number sense.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_flvc9by1">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_e2lxkh8n">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tqdnji8p">
                A cyclist is riding at a speed of <m>12</m> <em>km/h</em>, 
                and a motorcycle is moving at a speed of <m>20</m> <em>km/h</em> 
                on the same road in the same direction. 
                If the cyclist starts <m>100</m> meters ahead of the motorcycle, 
                how long will it take for the motorcycle to overtake the cyclist?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_dbedfjcr">
                Since the objects are moving in the same direction, 
                we calculate the relative speed by subtracting the cyclist's speed from the motorcycle's speed:
                    <md>
                    <mrow> Relative  Speed \amp = Speed  of   Motorcycle \, - \, Speed  of  Cyclist  </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jbp674qu">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 20 \, km/h \, - \, 12 \, km/h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>   
            <p xml:id="auto_lqivgir9">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 8 \, km/h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_36884l6h">           
                
                Now let's convert relative speed to meters per second, 
                so that we can work with the distance in meters, 
                we need to convert the relative speed from <em>km/h</em> to <em>m/s.</em>
                <md>
                    <mrow>Relative \, speed \amp = 8 \, km/h \times \frac{1000}{3600} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_c06xd8wg">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 2.22 \, m/s </mrow>
                </md>
                The initial distance between the motorcycle and the cyclist is 100 meters. 
                To calculate the time it will take for the motorcycle to overtake the cyclist,we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>Time \amp = \frac{Distance}{Relative \, Speed} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jzo8a9xs">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{100 \, m}{2.22 \, m/s} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_brsjd0et">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp \approx 45 \, seconds </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_x8itvgko">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_53tjvs26">
                A car travels at <m>60</m> <em>km/h</em>, and a truck travels at 
                <m>45</m> <em>km/h</em> in the same direction on a straight road. 
                If the car starts <m>150</m> meters behind the truck, 
                how long will it take for the car to overtake the truck
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_2opbw6tc">
                The relative speed between the car and the truck is:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Relative Speed} \amp = \text{Speed of Car} - \text{Speed of Truck} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xzgc4krr">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp =60 \, km/h - 45 \, km/h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qkobv4zg">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 15 \, km/h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ehntscxe">
                Convert Relative Speed to Meters per Second: Convert 15 km/h to m/s:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 15 \, km/h \times \frac{1000}{3600} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_d7d2tvve">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 4.17 \, m/s </mrow>
                </md>
                The initial distance between the car and the truck is 150 meters. 
                Use the formula to calculate the time:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Times} \amp = \frac{Distance}{Relative \, Speed} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_o10987hk">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{150 m}{4.17 \, m/s} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rkatp01o">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp \approx 36 \, seconds </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

